  "prompt": "To which class cin and cout belongs?",
  "response": "In C++, `cin` and `cout` are **objects** rather than classes. Here's a detailed breakdown:\n\n- **`std::cin`**:\n  - **Type**: `std::istream`\n  - **Description**: `cin` is an instance of the `std::istream` class, which is used for input operations. It is typically used to read data from the standard input (usually the keyboard).\n\n- **`std::cout`**:\n  - **Type**: `std::ostream`\n  - **Description**: `cout` is an instance of the `std::ostream` class, which is used for output operations. It is typically used to write data to the standard output (usually the screen).\n\nBoth `std::istream` and `std::ostream` inherit from the base class `std::ios`, which provides common functionalities for input and output streams.\n\n**Example Usage:**\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nint main() {\n    int number;\n    std::cout << \"Enter a number: \"; // Using std::cout (std::ostream)\n    std::cin >> number;             // Using std::cin (std::istream)\n    std::cout << \"You entered: \" << number << std::endl;\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\n**Namespaces:**\nBoth `cin` and `cout` are part of the `std` namespace, so they are typically accessed using the `std::` prefix unless the `using` directive is employed.\n\n**Summary:**\n- `cin` is an object of the `std::istream` class.\n- `cout` is an object of the `std::ostream` class.\n\nThese objects provide a convenient way to perform input and output operations in C++ programs.",
